Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board provided, we note that the black king on e5 is in check along the diagonal from white’s queen on c3 (the queen’s diagonal runs c3 → d4 → e5 → f6 → g7 → h8). Since none of the pawns can block or capture on that diagonal, we must move the king.

Evaluating the adjacent squares from e5:

• d4 is ruled out because it lies on the queen’s attacking diagonal.
• d6 and e6 are forbidden due to being adjacent to the white king on d7.
• f6 is also on the queen’s diagonal.
• That leaves d5, e4, f4, and f5 as possible king moves that are not adjacent to the white king and are not on the queen’s line.

For our move, we choose to move the king from e5 to d5, which in UCI format is written as "e5d5".

make_move e5d5

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, Black’s pieces are the king on h5 and a pawn on h3, while White only has the king on f6. As Black, you have several legal moves:
• King moves from h5 to g4, h4, or h6 (note that moves to g5 or g6 would place your king adjacent to the White king on f6, which isn’t allowed).
• Moving your pawn from h3 to h2 is also a possibility.

A good plan in such king-and-pawn endgames is to use your king actively—supporting your pawn's advance toward promotion while keeping the enemy king at bay. Moving your king from h5 to h6 is constructive because it keeps your king closer to the pawn’s critical promotion path while preventing the white king from coming dangerously close. 

I'll make the move: make_move h5h6

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I’ll go with a checking move using the queen that also prevents it from being captured. In this position the white king is on g8 and black’s queen is on h6 while the black king is on h5. By playing Qg6 (i.e. moving the queen from h6 to g6) we give check along the g‐file. Note that if the white king tries to capture on g6, it would move adjacent to the black king (from h5) which is illegal. (After Qg6+, white may try to move away, but none of its escape squares offer a safe haven.) 

So I’ll choose:
make_move h6g6

I'll inspect the current position:

──────────────────────────────
Board (assuming standard orientation with rank 8 at the top):

Rank 8:  a8 ⭘  b8 ⭘  c8 ⭘  d8 ⭘  e8 ⭘  f8 ⭘  g8 ⭘  h8 ⭘
Rank 7:  a7 ♟, b7 ⭘, c7 ⭘, d7 ⭘, e7 ♖, f7 ⭘, g7 ♟, h7 ⭘
Rank 6:  a6 ⭘, b6 ⭘, c6 ⭘, d6 ⭘, e6 ⭘, f6 ⭘, g6 ⭘, h6 ⭘
Rank 5:  a5 ⭘, b5 ⭘, c5 ⭘, d5 ♚, e5 ⭘, f5 ⭘, g5 ⭘, h5 ⭘
Rank 4:  a4 ♙, b4 ⭘, c4 ⭘, d4 ⭘, e4 ⭘, f4 ♔, g4 ⭘, h4 ⭘

Rank 2:  a2 ⭘, b2 ⭘, c2 ⭘, d2 ⭘, e2 ⭘, f2 ⭘, g2 ⭘, h2 ⭘
Rank 1:  a1 ⭘, b1 ⭘, c1 ⭘, d1 ⭘, e1 ⭘, f1 ⭘, g1 ⭘, h1 ⭘
──────────────────────────────

White’s pieces:
• King on f4 
• Rook on e7 
• Pawn on a4

Black’s pieces:
• King on d5 
• Pawns on a7 and g7

It’s Black’s turn. Let’s consider our options:

1. King moves:
   The Black king on d5 has potential moves to any adjacent square, but it must avoid squares that place it in check or adjacent to the White king (which sits on f4, so squares like e4, e5, etc. are off‐limits). Checking the adjacent candidates:
   • d5→c4, c5, c6, d4, d6, e4, e5, e6.
   • However, moving to any square adjacent to the White king is illegal. The White king at f4 covers e3, e4, e5, f3, f5, g3, g4, and g5. That eliminates e4 and e5.
   • Furthermore, note that moving to e6 would place our king in line with White’s rook on e7 along the e‐file (i.e. the rook on e7 controls e6), so that square is unsafe.
   Valid king moves then are: 
      • d5→c4 ("d5c4")
      • d5→c5 ("d5c5")
      • d5→c6 ("d5c6")
      • d5→d4 ("d5d4")
      • d5→d6 ("d5d6")

2. Pawn moves:
   For the pawn on a7:
      • One-square move: a7→a6 ("a7a6")
      • Two-square move is possible (if it’s still the pawn's first move): a7→a5 ("a7a5"), provided a6 and a5 are vacant.
   For the pawn on g7:
      • One-square move: g7→g6 ("g7g6")
      • Similarly, the two-step is available: g7→g5 ("g7g5") if the path is clear.

With these options in hand, a solid centralizing move for the king can improve our position. For instance,  King from d5 to d6 ("d5d6") steps out of the potential reach of White’s rook along the e‐file while keeping a safe distance from the White king.

I will now make the move:

make_move d5d6

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board position:

• White pieces:
 – Rook on a6
 – King on f6
 – Pawn on a4

• Black pieces:
 – King on d5

As black, your only piece is the king on d5. The king’s candidate moves from d5 are one square in any direction: c4, c5, c6, d4, d6, e4, e5, and e6. However, note:

1. The white king on f6 forbids moving to squares adjacent to it (namely e5, e6, f5, f7, g5, g6, and g7). Thus, e5 and e6 (from our candidate list) are excluded.
2. The white rook on a6 controls the entire sixth rank. Therefore, moves that land on rank 6 (i.e. c6 and d6) are under rook attack.
3. The remaining legal moves for your king are: c4, c5, d4, and e4.

A solid choice is to move the king to c5—to keep it central but away from potential rook checks along the sixth rank. 

Thus, you should play:

make_move d5c5

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board:

Rank 8: a8: White Rook, f8: Black King (in check by the rook along rank 8)  
Rank 7: all empty  
Rank 6: d6: White King  
Rank 2: a2, b2, c2: White Pawns  

Black’s only piece is the king on f8. The White Rook on a8 is checking along rank 8, so Black must move the king out of check. Evaluating the king’s possible moves from f8:

• Moving to e8 is not safe (same rank 8, attacked by the rook).  
• Moving to e7 is illegal because it’s adjacent to the White King on d6.  
• Moving to f7 is safe.  
• Moving to g7 is safe.  
• Moving to g8 remains on rank 8 (attacked by the rook).

Thus, a good move is to move the Black King from f8 to f7.

I'll now play:
make_move f8f7

Based on the board provided, Black’s only piece is the king at g8. It’s currently in check from the white rook on g7, which is attacking along the g–file. Considering the available king moves that remove the check:

• Moving to f8 (g8→f8) removes the king from the rook’s line.
• Moving to h8 (g8→h8) similarly removes the check.
• Capturing the rook with g8→g7 would simultaneously remove the checking piece.

Since capturing the rook wins material without exposing the king to further danger, I will choose that move.

make_move g8g7

Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

- 'get_legal_moves' to get a UCI formatted list of available moves
- 'make_move <UCI formatted move>' when you are ready to complete your turn (e.g., 'make_move e2e4')

get_legal_moves

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board provided, I note something interesting: White’s knight is currently posted on f7—deep in Black’s territory. This knight threatens to fork major Black pieces (for example, it can jump to d8 – where your queen sits – or h8 – where your rook is located). One effective way to neutralize this looming danger is to capture that intruding knight immediately.

When I examine the material, I see that Black’s king is on e8 and can move one square in any direction. f7 is diagonally adjacent to e8, so the Black king can capture the white knight on f7. Of course, before doing so I must be sure that landing on f7 wouldn’t expose the king to immediate danger (checks) from any other white pieces. Analyzing the white pieces – the queen on e2, the bishops on c1 and f1, the knight on b1, the rooks on a1 and h1, and the supportive pawns – I find that f7 does not appear to be under attack. Thus, capturing the white knight on f7 with the king is both legal and strategically sound, as it removes the immediate threat of a fork.

I now choose to make the move:

make_move e8f7

- 'get_legal_moves' to get a UCI formatted list of available moves
- 'make_move <UCI formatted move>' when you are ready to complete your turn (e.g., 'make_move e2e4')

⭘ ⭘ ♝ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ♔ ⭘

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, it appears that Black’s king on h7 is in check from White’s bishop on f5 (since the bishop is giving check along the diagonal f5–g6–h7). To address the check, Black has two options:
 
1. Move the king. The king on h7 can legally move to h6 (as g6 is attacked by the bishop, and g8/h8 fall under the rook’s control on e8).
2. Block the check by interposing a piece. Black’s pawn on g7 can move forward one square to g6, which would place it between the attacking bishop and the king.

Both are legal responses, but as a professional, I opt for the pawn move g7 to g6 because it blocks the check while also maintaining the king’s position.

make_move g7g6

Move made, switching player

    a  b  c  d  e  f  g  h

Here, White’s king sits on b6, Black’s king on e6, and Black has a pawn on f3. It’s Black’s turn.

A natural plan in king-and-pawn endgames is to push the pawn toward promotion when safely possible. With the Black pawn on f3, moving it forward to f2 brings it one step closer to the promotion square at f1. The white king on b6 is too far to reach f1 in time to stop this progress, and the Black king on e6 is in a good position to support the pawn if needed.

Thus, I choose to play the move:

make_move f3f2
